Flywireâ€™s repeat payment functionality is accessed via the [Flywire Checkout](/en/checkout/implementation/). The following guidance assumes 
that you are familiar with the available options for the checkout and will focus only on repeat payment options.

There are several different types of repeat payment model each providing different degrees of automation and customisation to suit your needs.

## Scheduled Payments

Using scheduled payments is the simplest way to instruct Flywire to collect future payments on specific dates for specific amounts. 
Using this model you redirect your customer to store their card details using the checkout and supply a future schedule of payments. 
You can then manage this schedule (e.g. edit amounts and dates, request card updates etc.) via your dashboard and the Flywire platform 
will process the payments and send communications on your behalf at the appropriate times.

### Sample Configuration

The following code sample shows how to configure the checkout to initiate a schedule of payments.

```js
var config = {
  env: "demo",
  recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",

  // Specifiy the returnUrl or an onCompleteCallback handler
  returnUrl: "https://httpbin.org/get",

  // Other checkout parameters (e.g. pass some payer info and set requestPayerInfo to true)
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  requestPayerInfo: true,

  // The amount must be 0 for scheduled payments
  amount: 0,

  // The payment schedule
  scheduledPayments: {
    type: "scheduled",
    data: {
      instalments: [
        {
          amount: 100.5,
          date: "2021-05-01",
        },
        {
          amount: 899.5,
          date: "2021-06-01",
        },
      ],
      serviceDescription: "Optional purpose of the payment"
    }
  }
};
```

The optional `serviceDescription` parameter is used to show you a description of the purpose of the payment in your dashboard.

<alert>

Values for the instalment `date` parameter must be passed in as future UTC dates. Payments are processed at 08:00 (8am) UTC every day.

</alert>

It is possible to schedule the capture of an immediate payment by specifiying todayâ€™s date (in the UTC timezone) which the platform will process 
immediately after storing the card details. To check the outcome of this payment you will need to log into your dashboard.

### Redirect or Callback

Once a the payer has successfully entered their details and the checkout modal is closed, control is passed back to to the host page using either the `returnUrl` or the `onCompleteCallback` handler as specified.

The following parameters are included either as parameters in the the query string or as the JSON args passed to the handler.

| Item           | Parameter        | Value                                                                               |
| -------------- | ---------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Status         | `status`         | e.g. `active` or `error`                                                            |
| Amount         | `amount`         | Will always be `0`                                                                  |
| Payment Method | `payment_method` | Will always be `scheduled`                                                          |
| Reference      | `reference`      | e.g. `2e828d42-9b90-4cbd-969c-7320bd559115` - a unique identifier for this schedule |

An example return URL is: http://httpbin.org/get?reference=2e828d42-9b90-4cbd-969c-7320bd559115&status=active&amount=0&payment_method=scheduled

An example of the args passed to the handler is:

```json
{
  "status": "active",
  "paymentMethod": "scheduled",
  "amount": 0,
  "reference": "2e828d42-9b90-4cbd-969c-7320bd559115"
}
```

### Schedule Management

Ongoing management of the schedule can only be undertaken from the Flywire dashboard. Please contact your account manager for 
access and/or training on how to do this.

## Tokenization

Tokenization provides you with the greatest degree of control and flexibility over future payment processing. In this model 
Flywire will simply ask your customer to enter their card details, securely save them in our PCI compliant vault and then give 
you a token back which you can then use to make future charges against their card by calling the charge endpoint.

### Card Capture

```js
var config = {
  env: "demo",
  recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",

  // The amount must be 0 for tokenization
  amount: 0,
  recurringType: "tokenization",

  // Specifiy the returnUrl or an onCompleteCallback handler
  returnUrl: "https://httpbin.org/get",

  // Other checkout parameters (e.g. pass payer info or set requestPayerInfo to true)
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  requestPayerInfo: true,

  // Optional (please see checkout documentation)
  locale: "en",
  callbackId: "REF1234",
  callbackUrl: "https://api.yourdomain.com/flywire-notifications",
};
```

To tokenize a card the `amount` parameter must be set to `0` and the `recurringType` to `tokenization` as shown above. Payer details 
can be passed in as paramters or the the `requestPayerInfo` can be set to `true` to prompt the payer to enter this information into the 
checkout window. There is no need to pass any [custom field](/en/checkout/implementation/#request-custom-field-info) information and any 
information you do pass will be ignored. Callbacks can be configured to allow you to receive payment status updates.

### Token Response

Once a the payer has successfully entered their details and the checkout modal is closed control is passed back to you either using 
the `returnUrl` or the `onCompleteCallback` handler.

The following parameters are included either as parameters in the the query string or as the JSON args passed to the handler.

| Item           | Parameter         | Value                                                        |
| -------------- | ----------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Status         | `status`          | e.g. `active` or `error`                                     |
| Amount         | `amount`          | Will always be `0`                                           |
| Payment Method | `payment_method`  | Will always be `recurring`                                   |
| Last 4 Digits  | `digits`          | e.g. `5454` - can be used to identify the card               |
| Expiry Month   | `expirationMonth` | e.g. `3`                                                     |
| Expiry Year    | `expirationYear`  | e.g. `2030`                                                  |
| Token          | `token`           | Store this to make future charges against the tokenized card |

An example return URL is: http://httpbin.org/get?status=success&amount=0&payment_method=recurring&token=ABCD1234&digits=5454&expirationMonth=3&expirationYear=2030

### Charging a Card

To charge a card you need to submit a `POST` request to the charge endpoint. The url of this endpoint varies by environment.

| Environment | URL                                                       |
| ----------- | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| Demo        | `https://checkout-api.demo.flywire.com/rest/payor/charge` |
| Prod        | `https://checkout-api.flywire.com/rest/payor/charge`      |

The content-type of the message should be application/json and the body should contain the the following parameters as a minimum.

```json
{
  "token": "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789",
  "amount": 100.0,
  "recipient": {
    "id": "Your 3-letter Portal Code",
    "fields": [
      {
        "id": "mandatory_custom_field_one",
        "value": "These fields will vary according to your portal configuration"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

Although the call is synchronous and the status is returned in the response it is also possible to hook into the 
standard [webhook notification service](/en/webhooks/notifications-v1/) for payments by supplying both a callback id and url as follows.

<alert>
Please note that tokenized payment callbacks are currently only sent using version 1 of the notifcations.
</alert>

```json
{
  "token": "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789",
  "amount": 100.0,
  "recipient": {
    "id": "Your 3-letter Portal Code",
    "fields": [
      {
        "id": "mandatory_custom_field_one",
        "value": "These fields will vary according to your portal configuration"
      }
    ]
  },
  "callback": {
    "id": "REF1234",
    "url": "https://api.your-domain.com/flywire-notifications"
  }
}
```

Finally, if you captured the original card holder details and know these have been updated since the initial card tokenization, 
these values should be supplied for **all** subsequent charges against the card.

```json
{
  "token": "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789",
  "amount": 100.0,
  "recipient": {
    "id": "Your 3-letter Portal Code",
    "fields": [
      {
        "id": "mandatory_custom_field_one",
        "value": "These fields will vary according to your portal configuration"
      }
    ]
  },
  "callback": {
    "id": "REF1234",
    "url": "https://api.your-domain.com/flywire-notifications"
  },
  "sender": {
    "fields": [
      {
        "id": "first_name",
        "value": "John"
      },
      {
        "id": "last_name",
        "value": "Doe"
      },
      {
        "id": "address1",
        "value": "10, Downing St."
      },
      {
        "id": "city",
        "value": "London"
      },
      {
        "id": "country",
        "value": "GB"
      },
      {
        "id": "phone",
        "value": "+44 1234 567 890"
      },
      {
        "id": "email",
        "value": "john.doe@flywire.com"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

### Charge Responses

You should use the HTTP response code to determine if a charge was successful. In most scenarios additional details is 
contained in the response body and is formatted as `application/json`.

#### HTTP 201

The call to charge the card has been successful. The payment reference is contained in the body.

```json
{
  "status": "success",
  "reference": "FLY1234567890"
}
```

If you supplied a callback url and id to subscribe to notifications then these will fire too.

#### HTTP 400

Bad request. The message body is malformed. A non-exhaustive list of the more common issues follows.

**1. Configuration Error**

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "Configuration issue"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Possible Causes**

- Amount too big
- Amount too small
- No payment options available

Please contact your account manager if you receive this error.

**2. Missing or Empty Token**

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "token required"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Possible Causes**

- Missing token parameter
- Empty or null token value

**3. Invalid Token**

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "Bad token"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Possible Causes**

- Invalid token value

**4. Missing or Empty Amount**

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "amount required"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Possible Causes**

- Missing amount parameter
- Empty or null amount value

**5. Invalid Amount**

```json
Invalid input
```

The response body in this instance is not formatted as JSON

**Possible Causes**

- Non-numeric amount value

**6. Invalid Recipient**

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "Bad recipient"
    }
  ]
}
```

The response body in this instance is not formatted as JSON

**Possible Causes**

- Incorrect recipient code used for the supplied token

#### HTTP 404

Recipient not found. This error is returned if the recipient code used doesnâ€™t match any record.

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "{\"errors\":[{\"type\":\"not_found\",\"message\":\"resource not found\"}]}"
    }
  ]
}
```

#### HTTP 422

Validation errors. Each error in the arry will contain details of the specific validation rule that has been violated. The format is as follows:

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "string",
      "param": "string",
      "source": "string",
      "type": "string"
    }
  ]
}
```

#### HTTP 500

Unknown error.

```json
Unknown error encountered while charging the payor.
```

**Possible Causes**

- The response body in this instance is not formatted as JSON

## Overview 

If you want to maintain complete control of the customer data capture within your site then the Flywire checkout 
offers the most streamlined payment experience available. Customers remain on your site and the checkout modal 
pop-up allows the payer to chose their payment method and complete the payment in as little as one step.

On completion of a payment the customer is returned back to your site to a specified redirection URL or through a 
callback function. In addition, real-time notifications can be enabled to allow you update your back-office systems 
with payment status information.

There are several configuration options available when using the Flywire checkout. Please take a look at 
the following sample page and configuration options to decide which is most appropriate for your use case. 
All the available configuration options are explained [here](/en/checkout/implementation/#configuration-parameters).

## Sample Page

This is a simplified sample page demonstrating how to initiate a payment through Flywire.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <!-- Include the flywire.js script -->
    <script src="https://checkout.flywire.com/flywire-payment.js"></script>
  </head>

  <body>
    <!-- Add a button element -->
    <button onclick="pay()">
      Make Payment
    </button>

    <script>
      // Add an event handler
      function pay() {

        var config = {
          // See sample configuration options
        };

        var modal = window.FlywirePayment.initiate(config);
        modal.render();
      }
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```

### Script

Add the flywire-payment script to your page

```html
 <!-- Include the flywire.js script -->
 <script src="https://checkout.flywire.com/flywire-payment.js"></script>
```

### Event Handler

Add a button (or other element or event) to trigger the Flywire checkout

```html
    <!-- Add a button element -->
    <button onclick="pay()">
      Make Payment
    </button>

    <script>
      // Add an event handler
      function pay() {
```

### Configuration

Set your portal specific payment configuration options. Please refer to the samples [here](#sample-configurations).

```js
        var config = {
          // See sample configuration options
        };
```

### Render

Finally, initiate the payment with the specified configuration and render the checkout.

```js
        var modal = window.FlywirePayment.initiate(config);
        modal.render();
    }
 </script>
```

## Sample Configurations

### Minimum

The following parameters must be specified as a minimum to successfully render the checkout.

The customer will be prompted to enter all payer and custom field information. 

We recommended that you always implement an `onInvalidInput` handler to report any error messages to your customers.

```js
var config = {
  // Set the target environment (demo, prod)
  env: "demo",

  // Set your unique code (may differ between demo and prod)
  recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",

  // Set the value of the payment to be processed
  amount: 1234.56,

  // Recommended (not required) validation error handler
  onInvalidInput: function(errors) {
    errors.forEach(function(error) {
      alert(error.msg);
    });
  },

  // Display payer and custom field input boxes
  requestPayerInfo: true,
  requestRecipientInfo: true,

  // Set the return URL where payers are redirected to on completion
  returnUrl: "https://httpbin.org/get"
};
```

### Partial Payer Info

This sample configuration will render a checkout with information input boxes partially populated by the values in the configuration object. 

If complete information is provided for either the payer information or for custom fields then thoses pages will be skipped by setting the 
`skipCompletedSteps` to `true`. 

Once the payment is complete the `onCompleteCallback` handler will be called and the checkout closed rather than the window being redirected.

```js
var config = {
  env: "demo",
  recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",
  amount: 1234.56,

  onInvalidInput: function(errors) {
    errors.forEach(function(error) {
      alert(error.msg);
    });
  },

  // Display the payer and custom information input boxes
  // skipping either page if all the information has been passed in.
  // NB. You can see this behaviour by completing the address, city and
  // country parameters in the next block.
  requestPayerInfo: true,
  requestRecipientInfo: true,
  skipCompletedSteps: true,

  // Pass in partial payer information (missing parameters can
  // alternatively be omitted rather than included with empty or
  // null values)
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  email: "john.doe@flywire.com",
  phone: "+44 1234 567 890",
  address: "",
  city: "",
  country: null,

  // Pass in partial custom field information (missing parameters can
  // alternatively be omitted rather than included with empty or null
  // values)
  recipientFields: {
    booking_reference: "REF1234",
    additional_information: null,
  },

  // The callback function that is called once the payment is complete
  onCompleteCallback: function(args) {
    alert(args);
  }
};
```

### Complete Payer Info

This sample configuration will render a checkout without showing any input boxes by setting both the `requestPayerInfo` 
and `requestRecipientInfo` parameters to `false`. 

It is important to provide an `onInvalidInput` handler in this instance to ensure any validation errors are reported 
back to the payer. 

In addition a `nonce` parameter can be set that is included in the generation of the sig parameter included in 
the `returnUrl` (and in the args supplied to the `onCompleteCallback` handler). We recommend that you set this to a value
that uniquely identifies an entity in your platform that this payment relates to - e.g. the same value 
as `booking_reference` in the sample below.

```js
var config = {
  env: "demo",
  recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",
  amount: 1234.56,

  // Highly recommended for this configuration
  onInvalidInput: function(errors) {
    errors.forEach(function(error) {
      alert(error.msg);
    });
  },

  // Hide the information input boxes
  requestPayerInfo: false,
  requestRecipientInfo: false,

  // Pass in complete payer information
  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  email: "john.doe@flywire.com",
  phone: "+44 1234 567 890",
  address: "10, Downing St.",
  city: "London",
  country: "GB",

  // Pass in complete custom field information
  recipientFields: {
    booking_reference: "REF1234",
    additional_information: "This is a sample",
  },

  // Supply a nonce to be included in the signature generation
  nonce: "REF1234",

  returnUrl: "https://httpbin.org/get"
};
```

### Webhooks

This sample configuration includes the parameters to setup payment status webhook notifications to be sent to your 
servers.

Notifications are POSTed to the URL specified in the `callbackUrl` parameter and will contain a payload 
that includes the value specified in the `callbackId` parameter. To trigger webhook notifications **both** these parameters 
must be supplied.

As with the `nonce` parameter, we recommend that you set this to a value that uniquely identifies an entity 
in your platform that this payment relates to - e.g. the same value as `booking_reference` in the sample below.

There are 2 versions of callbacks currently supported.
- Version 1 (Default)
- Version 2

For new implementations we recommend using ``callbackVersion: "2"`` as these notifications contain additional 
information and status transitions.

<alert type='warning'>
For backwards compatibility we default to use version 1 of the callbacks 
</alert>

```js
var config = {
  env: "demo",
  recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",
  amount: 1234.56,

  onInvalidInput: function(errors) {
    errors.forEach(function(error) {
      alert(error.msg);
    });
  },

  requestPayerInfo: true,
  requestRecipientInfo: true,

  returnUrl: "https://httpbin.org/get",

  // Enable payment status notification callbacks
  callbackId: "REF1234",
  callbackUrl: "https://api.yourdomain.com/flywire-notifications",
  callbackVersion: "2"
};
```

### Typical

This configuration shows typical parameters that allows you to leverage the data capture and validation provided 
by Flywire, a custom sort order for payment options as well as setting up webhook notifications and secure, 
verifiable signature generation.

```js
var config = {
  env: "demo",
  recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",
  amount: 1234.56,

  onInvalidInput: function(errors) {
    errors.forEach(function(error) {
      alert(error.msg);
    });
  },

  requestPayerInfo: true,
  requestPayerInfo: true,
  skipCompletedSteps: true,

  // Set any custom fields to read-only to prevent payers changing values
  // (in this configuration 'additional_information' will be editable)
  readonlyFields: ["booking_reference", "client_id"],

  firstName: "John",
  lastName: "Doe",
  email: "john.doe@flywire.com",
  phone: "+44 1234 567 890",
  address: "10, Downing St.",
  city: "London",
  country: "GB",

  recipientFields: {
    booking_reference: "REF1234",
    client_id: "CLI1234",
    additional_information: null,
  },

  // Show the cheapest local payment option first but prefer bank transfers
  // over cards and online methods if they are the same price
  paymentOptionsConfig: {
    sort: [
      { currency: ["local", "foreign"] },
      { amount: "asc" },
      { type: ["bank_transfer", "credit_card", "online"] },
    ],
  },

  nonce: "REF1234",
  returnUrl: "https://httpbin.org/get",

  callbackId: "REF1234",
  callbackUrl: "https://api.yourdomain.com/flywire-notifications",
  callbackVersion: "2"
};
```

## Configuration Parameters

Most of the configuration parameters have been demonstrated in the sample configuration blocks above. 
Usage of each of these as well as some additional parameters are described in detail here.

### Environment

By default our demo environment will be used if no `env` parameter is supplied.

#### Available Values
- `demo` (Default)
- `prod`

```js
// Set the target environment (demo, prod)
env: "demo",
```

### Recipient Code

The `recipientCode` parameter takes the 3 letter code that directs a request through to the appropriate 
Flywire payment portal. This may differ between your demo and production environments.

```js
// Set your unique code (may differ between demo and prod)
recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",
```

### Amount

In order to successfully initiate a payment and load the Flywire checkout the `amount` parameter must be set.

```js
// Set the value of the payment to be processed
amount: 1234.56,
```

### Input Validation

If any of the information passed to the checkout does not pass validation then an array of error objects will 
be returned to `onInvalidInput` callback function. 

In the case where invalid payer information is passed to the 
checkout and `requestPayerInfo` or `requestRecipientInfo` is set to ``true`` the payer will be able to correct any 
invalid details within the checkout.

```js
// Recommended but not required - include a validation callback.
// Please provide your own validation reporting feature rather
// than alerting the user and logging to the console.
onInvalidInput: function (errors) {
    errors.forEach(function(error) {
        alert(error.msg);
    });
},
```

Below is an example of the errors array that is passed as an argument into the function.

```json
[
  {
    id: "email",
    msg: "Please enter a valid email address",
    msgId: "emailConstraintNotice",
  },
  {
    id: "amount",
    msg: "Required",
    msgId: "validation.required",
  },
  {
    id: "amount",
    msg: "Invalid amount format",
    msgId: "validation.invalidAmountFormat",
  },
];
```

Messages in the `msg` field will be translated into the language set by the `locale` parameter when initiating 
the checkout. Please use the `msgId` field to test for and handle specific error types.

<alert>

  You can view metadata related to all the fields required in the configuration object by checking the
  ``window.FlywirePayment.fields`` object in the browser console after the flywire-payment.js script has loaded.

</alert>

### Payer Info

Payer information can be set by including the following parameters.

```js
// Pass in payer information
firstName: "John",
lastName: "Doe",
email: "john.doe@flywire.com",
phone: "+44 1234 567 890",
address: "10, Downing St.",
city: "London",
country: "GB",
```

### Custom Info

For any custom fields that have been added to you portal this information can be set by including the `recipientFields` parameter.

```js
// Pass in portal specific custom fields
recipientFields: {
  booking_reference: "REF1234"
},
```

<alert>

  These fields vary by portal - please check your specific portal configuration to view your available fields.

</alert>

### Request Payer Info

If you would like Flywire to capture either all or any missing or invalid payer information as part of the checkout process 
you should set the `requestPayerInfo` parameter to `true`. 

Alternatively you should set it to `false` (or omit the parameter) and supply the payer information values in the 
configuration object. 

If you set the value to false you should implment an `onInvalidInput` handler to display any validation errors to the payer.

#### Available Values
- `true`
- `false` (Default)

<alert type='warning'>

  Please note that the country should be the **2-letter ISO country code**

</alert>

```js
// Display the payer information input boxes
requestPayerInfo: true,

// Pass in partial payer information (missing parameters can
// alternatively be omitted rather than included with empty
// values)
firstName: "John",
lastName: "Doe",
email: "john.doe@flywire.com",
phone: "+44 1234 567 890",
address: "",
city: "",
country: "",
```

Alternatively all of the following fields must be supplied with values. 

```js
// Hide the payer information input boxes
requestPayerInfo: false,

// Pass in complete payer information
firstName: "John",
lastName: "Doe",
email: "john.doe@flywire.com",
phone: "+44 1234 567 890",
address: "10, Downing St.",
city: "London",
country: "GB",

// Implement an error handler
onInvalidInput: function (errors) {
    errors.forEach(function(error) {
        alert(error.msg);
    });
},
```



### Request Custom Info

If you would like Flywire to capture either all or any missing or invalid custom fields as part of the checkout 
process you should set the `requestRecipientInfo` parameter to `true`. 

Alternatively you should set it to `false` (or omit the parameter) and supply all the `recipientFields` information 
in the configuration object. 

If you set `requestRecipientInfo` to `false` you should implment an `onInvalidInput` handler to display any validation 
errors to the payer.

#### Available Values

- `true`
- `false` (Default)

```js
// Display the custom field input boxes
requestRecipientInfo: true,

// Pass in partial recipientFields information (missing parameters can
// alternatively be omitted rather than included with empty values)
recipientFields: {
    booking_reference: ""
}
```

Alternatively all of the required fields must be supplied with values.

```js
// Hide the custom field input boxes
requestRecipientInfo: false,

// Pass in complete payer information
recipientFields: {
    booking_reference: "REF1234"
},

// Implement an error handler
onInvalidInput: function (errors) {
    errors.forEach(function(error) {
        alert(error.msg);
    });
},
```

### Read Only

If you would like any fields to be read-only (e.g. firstName, country etc..) you can use the `readonlyFields` array 
to specify which fields you would like to be un-editable.

These fields can be either the payer info or custom info fields.

```js
// Pass in all portal specific required custom fields
firstName: "John",
lastName: "Doe",
country: "US",

requestPayerInfo: true,
requestRecipientInfo: true,

recipientFields: {
    booking_reference: "REF1234"
},

readonlyFields: [
    "firstName",
    "lastName",
    "country",
    "booking_reference"
],
```

### Skip Steps

In order to avoid payers clicking through unnecessary steps in the checkout you can set the `skipCompletedSteps` 
parameter to ``true`` alongside the `requestPayerInfo` and `requestRecipientInfo` parameters as necessary. 

This is useful if you are unsure whether either the payer details or custom field values you supply will be complete or 
partial. 

With this set to `true` if all the required information has been supplied the checkout process will jump 
to the next step automatically. 

There is also the option to skip only a certain step. You can do this by specifying the step name. For example 
you can skip the custom fields step if it has been completed by specifying `['requestRecipientInfo']`.

#### Available Values

- `true`
- `false` (Default)
- `[step name]` (`'requestPayerInfo'` or `'requestRecipientInfo'`)

```js
 // Display the payer and custom information input boxes
 // skipping either page if all the information has been passed in.
 requestPayerInfo: true,
 requestRecipientInfo: true,
 skipCompletedSteps: true,
```

<alert type='warning'>

You should not use ``skipCompletedSteps`` if you want to give the payer the chance to edit the fields information.

</alert>

### Filtering

By default Flywire will show all available payment options for a given a portal during checkout. 

In certain circumstances it may be desirable to restrict the methods available to your customers based on a set of rules (e.g. only accept bank 
transfers for payments overs a certain value, only show card payments a certain time before a booking etc).

To enable this the Flywire checkout allows you to filter the payment options offered by payment type and by payer currency.
Filters are supplied in the `paymentOptionsConfig`  parameter.

#### Available Payment Type Filters

- `bank_transfer`
- `credit_card` (Show all card payment options e.g. debit cards)
- `online` (Show all online alternative payment options e.g. PayPal)

#### Availble Currency Filters

- `local` (Only show payment options in the payers local currency e.g. only GBP options for a payer in the UK)
- `foreign` (Only show payment options not in the payers local currency e.g. everything but GBP options for a payer in the UK)
- `fx` (Only show payment options that are a different currency to the collection currency)
- `nonFX` (Only show payment options that are in the same currency as the collection currency)

```js
paymentOptionsConfig: {
    // Only allow local card and online payments
    filters: {
        type: ['online', 'credit_card'],
        currency: ['fx']
    }
}
```

### Sorting

Flywire makes every effort to display the payment option to payers in the most appropriate order based on payer 
behaviour. 

However, we recognise that you may prefer to change this order to better suit yours and your payers needs. 

To enable this the Flywire checkout allows you to sort the payment options offered by payment type, payment currency and/or amount.
The sort orders are supplied in the `paymentOptionsConfig`  parameter.

#### Availble Payment Type Sort Options

- `bank_transfer`
- `credit_card`
- `online` (This refers to online alternative payment options e.g. PayPal)

#### Availble Currency Sort Options

- `local` (The payers local currency)
- `foreign` (Not the payers local currency)

#### Availble Amount Sort Options

- `asc` (ascending amount order)
- `desc` (descending amount order)

```js
paymentOptionsConfig: {
  // Show the cheapest local payment option first but prefer bank transfers
  // over cards and online methods if they are the same price
  sort: [
    { currency: ["local", "foreign"] },
    { amount: "asc" },
    { type: ["bank_transfer", "credit_card", "online"] },
  ];
}
```

<alert>

The order in which ``type``, ``currency`` and ``amount`` are set in the sort array affects the final sort order.

</alert>

### Nonce

Flywire includes a `sig` parameter in query string of the return URL and in the args supplied to the `onCompleteCallback` handler.

To include your own parameter in the generation of the signature please supply a value to the `nonce` parameter. 

We recommend that you set this to a value that uniquely identifies the entity in your platform that this payment relates 
to - e.g. a booking reference, reservation number, registration id etc.

```js
// Supply a nonce to be used in signature generation
nonce: "REF1234",
```

Details of how to verify the signature can be found in the [verify signature](/en/checkout/implementation/#signature-verification) 
section.

### Return URL

Once a payment is completed the checkout modal is closed. If you have specified a value for the 
return URL the page will be redirect to the URL specified in the `returnUrl` parameter.

```js
// Set the return URL where payers are redirected to on completion
returnUrl: "https://httpbin.org/get";
```

The following parameters are included in the query string of the `returnUrl`

| Item | Parameter | Value |
|---|---|---|
| Reference | reference | e.g. ``FLY123456789`` |
| Status | status | Possible values are ``pending``, ``success``, ``error`` |
| Amount | amount | e.g. 1234.56 |
| Payment Method | payment_method | Possible values are ``bank_transfer``, ``online`` |
| Nonce (if supplied) | payment_method | e.g. ``REF1234`` |
| Signature | sig | Please refer to the [verify signature](/en/checkout/implementation/#signature-verification) section |

<alert>

The ``pending`` status always returned when the payer initates a bank transfer and never returned for online payments.

</alert>


An example return URL is:

http://httpbin.org/get?reference=FLY123567890&status=success&amount=1234.56&payment_method=online&_=REF1234&sig=abcdefgh


### onCompleteCallback

An alternative to using the `returnUrl` is to specify a function as the `onCompleteCallback` parameter. When 
this is done, control is passed back to this function once the modal has closed.

<alert type='warning'>

You should only include a value for either the ``returnUrl`` parameter or for the ``onCompleteCallback`` parameter, never both.

</alert>

```js
// The callback function that is called once the payment is complete
onCompleteCallback: function(args) {
    console.log(args);
}
```

The following parameters are included as properties of the args object passed to the `onCompleteCallback` handler.

| Item | Parameter | Value |
|---|---|---|
| Reference | reference | e.g. ``FLY123456789`` |
| Status | status | Possible values are ``pending``, ``success``, ``error`` |
| Amount | amount | e.g. 1234.56 |
| Payment Method | payment_method | Possible values are ``bank_transfer``, ``online`` |
| Nonce (if supplied) | payment_method | e.g. ``REF1234`` |
| Signature | sig | Please refer to the [verify signature](/en/checkout/implementation/#signature-verification) section |

<alert>

The ``pending`` status always returned when the payer initates a bank transfer and never returned for online payments.

</alert>


An example of the args passed to the handler is:

```js
{
    reference: "FLY1234567890",
    status: "success",
    amount: "1234.56",
    paymentMethod: "online",
    _: "REF1234",
    sig: "abcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890abcdef1234567890"
}
```

### onCancel

In some instances it may be useful to handle a payer closing the checkout window by clicking the ``X`` button. 

Should you need to handle this event you can supply an `onCancel` callback.

```js
// The callback function that is called once the payment is complete
onCancel: function() {
    console.log("Checkout cancelled");
}
```

### Modal Handle

Should you need to keep a reference to the checkout window in order to close it programatically you can get the handle to 
the checkout modal from the `inititate` function.

The window handle has two functions availale on it `render()` and `close()`.

```js
var modal = window.FlywirePayment.initiate(config);
modal.render();

setTimeout(function() {
  modal.close();
  console.log("Checkout closed after 10 seconds");
}, 10 * 1000);
```

### Extended Validation

Flywire performs quality checks on the information provided for every payment.

In cases where the information provided doesnâ€™t pass our validation checks it will be processed but then placed in a quality 
check queue. To reduce the chances of payments being held in this queue the Flywire checkout validates the information provided 
up-front and alert payers to any potential validation errors before processing.

Should you wish to disable this feature you can set the `skipMQC` parameter to `true`.

#### Available Values
- `true`
- `false` (Default)

```js
// Skip the quality check validation rules
skipMQC: true,
```

### Split Payments

If you would like Flywire to automatically distribute part of the payment amount to one or more of your partners 
(that must also be enrolled with Flywire) you can use the `payables` parameter to set up split payments. 

Each payable takes the amount specified in the payable away from the `amount` of the payment and pays it out to the specified recipient. 
The following parameters make up a split payment configuration within the `payables` array.

| Item | Parameter | Value |
|---|---|---|
| Amount | amount | e.g. ``10.00`` (mandatory) - must not exceed the base amount |
| Recipient | recipient | e.g. ``FWB`` (mandatory) - 3 letter Partner Portal code |
| Description | description | e.g. ``Commission for booking ref. 123456`` |

```js
// The base portal code - any remaining amount left after the payables
// distribution will be sent to this account (in this instance 70.00)
recipientCode: "Your Portal Code",

// The base (total) amount charged to the payer
amount: 100.00,

// Split payments configuration
payables: [
    {
        // Subtracted from the base of 100.00
        amount: 10.00,
        recipient: "First Partner Portal Code",
        description: "First partner payment description"
    },
    {
        // Subtracted from the base of 100.00
        amount: 20.00,
        recipient: "Second Partner Portal Code",
        description: "Second partner payment description"
    }
]
```

Please bear in mind the following constraints when using split payments.
- The `payables` array must contain at least one element.
- The `payables` array cannot include duplicate `recipient`â€™s.
- Each `recipient` must be a valid Flywire 3 letter code and cannot be be the same as the base payment `recepientCode`.
- The sum of all payable `amount` parameters must not exceed the base payment amount.

### Locale

The language of the payment experience can be fixed by supplying the locale parameter. If this value is 
omittred (recommended) then the browser language will be used (where supported)

#### Available Values

- `en` (English)
- `es` (Spanish)
- `fr` (French)
- `id` (Indonesian)
- `ja` (Japanese)
- `ko` (Korean)
- `pt` (Portuguese)
- `vi` (Vietnamese)
- `zh` (Chinese)

```js
// Set the locale the checkout should be displayed in
locale: "en",
```

### Webhook Notifications

The â€‹`callbackUrl`, `callbackId` are optional parameters for systems that require real-time payment status updates to 
be POSTed to their servers. To use callbacks you must set values for **both**  of these parameters

The `callbackUrl` should be a publicly accessible endpoint. 

We recommend that you set the `callbackId` to a value that uniquely identifies the entity in your platform that this 
payment relates to - e.g. a booking reference, reservation number, registration id etc.

There are 2 `callbackVersion` values currently supported.
- `"1"` (Default) - please read [v1. Notifications](/en/webhooks/notifications-v1/)
- `"2"` (Recommended) - please read [v2. Notifications](/en/webhooks/notifications-v2/)

<alert type='warning'>

For backwards compatibility we default to use version 1 of the callbacks however, we recommend that you use the latest 
version (currently version 2) as these notifications contain additional information and status transitions.

</alert>

```js
// Enable payment status notification callbacks
callbackUrl: "https://api.your-domain.com/flywire-notifications",
callbackId: "REF1234",
callbackVersion: "2"
```

Please refer to the webhooks documentation for details on how to process notifications.

## Signature Verification

In order to verify that the parameters included in the `returnUrl` and the args supplied to the `onCompleteCallback` handler, 
Flywire includes a `sig` parameter.

This is signature is the SHA256 hash of the parameters plus a shared secret. Please contact your account manager to 
arrange the transfer of your shared secret.

<alert type='warning'>

You should only ever verify the signature on your server and you should **never send your shared secret to the clientâ€™s browser**.

</alert>

<code-group>
  <code-block label="Javascript" active>

```js
const crypto = require("crypto");

//
// Retrieve this value from your settings
//
const sharedSecret = "1234567890123456789012345678901234567890";

//
// Retrieve these values from the returnURL query string params
//
const _ = "REF1234";
const reference = "FLY1234567890";
const status = "success";
const amount = "1234.56";
const paymentMethod = "online";
const sig = "631da0e951478c11bcb9831764de45c21a9c79d2a3b76361dd57a7127219ebcb";

//
// Regenerate the signature locally
//
const data = _ + sharedSecret + reference + status + amount + paymentMethod;
const signature = generateSignature(data);

//
// Compare and continue
//
if (signature === sig) {
  console.log("Match");
}

//
// Utility function
//
function generateSignature(data, sharedSecret) {
  const hash = crypto.createHash("sha256");
  hash.update(data);

  return hash.digest("hex");
}
```

  </code-block>
  <code-block label="PHP">


```php
<?php
//
// Retrieve this value from your settings
//
$sharedSecret = '1234567890123456789012345678901234567890';

//
// Retrieve these values from the returnURL query string params
//
$nonce = 'REF1234';
$reference = 'FLY1234567890';
$status = 'success';
$amount = '1234.56';
$paymentMethod = 'online';
$sig = '631da0e951478c11bcb9831764de45c21a9c79d2a3b76361dd57a7127219ebcb';

//
// Regenerate the signature locally
//
$payload = $nonce . $sharedSecret . $reference . $status . $amount . $paymentMethod;
$compiledSignature = hash('sha256', $payload);

//
// Compare and continue
//
if($sig == $compiledSignature){
  print "Match";
}
?>
